{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The request sent to the external API always includes the complete list of valid taxonomy labels.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"A pure unit test of prompt-builder logic can miss failures in wiring/serialization between classifier module and API client. The real failure boundary is the outbound request payload as emitted by integrated modules.","test_description":"Run the classifier against a local fake API endpoint that records raw requests. Assert each request contains the full configured taxonomy label set (no missing/extra labels), independent of label order.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.55,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When the API returns a label that is not in the taxonomy, the module returns \"unknown\" instead of forwarding the unexpected value to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure is often at response parsing + taxonomy validation boundary. A narrow unit test of only the validator could pass while integrated parsing/normalization still leaks invalid labels.","test_description":"Use a local fake API to return a syntactically valid response containing an out-of-taxonomy label. Verify the module returns exactly \"unknown\" and never exposes the raw invalid label.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.4,"Integration":0.5,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The classification result for the same document is the same across repeated calls.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Correctness depends on real model output stability (non-determinism). Mocked or deterministic stubs cannot reveal real drift/variance across repeated calls.","test_description":"Call the real AI classification API repeatedly (e.g., 50-100 runs) with the same document and production prompt/settings. Assert labels are identical across runs (or meet the contract threshold if defined).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.2,"Agentic":0.65,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The number of tokens consumed for a typical document stays within the configured per-call budget.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"If you mock token accounting, you can hide real over-budget failures caused by provider-side tokenization/usage accounting differences. This needs a real API call and real usage data.","test_description":"Send representative documents to the real API in a controlled test environment and read provider-reported usage tokens. Assert per-call usage is <= configured budget.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.25,"System":0.55,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the API signals that the request rate is too high, the module waits and retries rather than returning an error to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"A pure mock can miss HTTP/status/header handling and retry wiring. A local test server exercising real client retry flow is sufficient; no real external API or model behavior is required.","test_description":"Use a local fake API that returns rate-limit responses (e.g., 429 with Retry-After) before a success response. Verify the module delays, retries, and eventually returns success instead of surfacing an immediate error.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.13,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}}]}
